# Change log — mark (pushed) + open next section after commit + push

When you **`git commit`** and **`git push`** successfully in the same task (because the user asked you to commit/push, or to ship the current batch):

1. Open **`GoDiveMVP/cursor/change_log.md`**.
2. Find the **highest-numbered** `## NN - …` section that is **not** already marked **`(pushed)`**.
3. Mark it **`(pushed)`**:
   - Put **`(pushed)`** on the section header line (same style as §20: `## 21 - Title **(pushed)**`).
   - Remove a standalone **`(not pushed)`** line under the header if present.
4. Add the **next** section immediately below (increment **`NN`** by 1):
   - Header only: **`## NN - …`** with a short title (e.g. **Next batch**). No **`(pushed)`** marker.
   - Leave the body **empty** so future work appends there.
   - Update the file intro if it still describes the old “ask for a new section” workflow.
5. **Include** the updated **`change_log.md`** in the commit when possible; if the push already happened, make a small follow-up commit with the mark + new section, or amend only if your commit rules allow and the prior commit was yours and unpushed.

## Do not

- Mark **`(pushed)`** if **`git push`** failed, was skipped, or only a local commit exists without a successful push the user requested.
- Skip opening the **next** empty section after a successful push the user requested (unless they explicitly say not to).
- Mark multiple sections in one push unless the user says several batches shipped together.

## With changelog sync

This complements **`.cursor/rules/changelog-app-summary-sync.mdc`**: doc updates for the work still happen **before** commit; **`(pushed)`** + the new section header are the post-push bookkeeping step.
